This is a complete A–Z breakdown of how to run Claude Opus 4.8 and Kimi K2.7 together — using each one for exactly what it's best at, and paying a fraction of what you'd pay running Opus alone.
Bookmark this before you forget.
The Mistake Almost Everyone Makes
You pick one model and route everything through it.
If you picked Opus 4.8, you're paying $5 input / $25 output per million tokens for tasks a $0.95 model could handle just as well.

If you picked Kimi, you're occasionally hitting tasks where you really do want the absolute frontier of reasoning quality — and you're not getting it.
The smart play isn't picking one. It's routing.
Some tasks are high-volume, mechanical, and token-heavy — they belong on Kimi K2.7. Some tasks are rare, high-stakes, and require the best reasoning available — they belong on Opus 4.8.
Run both. Route by task. Pay 80% less for the same output quality.
Here's the exact system.
What Each Model Actually Is
Kimi K2.7 Code — released June 12, 2026. Open-weight, 1-trillion-parameter MoE model (32B active, 384 experts), 256K context. Built specifically for long-horizon agentic coding.
The key number: it uses roughly 30% fewer reasoning tokens than K2.6 while scoring higher on coding benchmarks. Moonshot reports +21.8% on Kimi Code Bench v2, +11.0% on Program Bench, +31.5% on MLS Bench Lite.
Pricing: $0.95 input / $4.00 output per million tokens. Cached input drops to $0.19.
Claude Opus 4.8 — Anthropic's most capable generally-available model before Fable 5. State-of-the-art reasoning, the gold standard for complex multi-step work where quality cannot be compromised.
Pricing: $5 input / $25 output per million tokens.
The price gap: Opus is roughly 5x more expensive on input, 6x more expensive on output.
A note on the benchmarks: every K2.7 number so far is Moonshot's own proprietary benchmark. As of mid-June 2026, there are no independent third-party numbers on SWE-bench Verified, Terminal-Bench, or LiveCodeBench. Treat the scores as vendor-reported and directional. Test on your own code before trusting them.
The Core Principle: Route by Task Type
The entire workflow comes down to one decision made per task:
Does this task require the absolute best reasoning available, or does it require lots of competent work done cheaply?
If it's the first — Opus 4.8. If it's the second — Kimi K2.7.
Most work is the second kind. That's why the savings are real.
What Goes on Kimi K2.7
These are the high-volume, token-heavy, mechanical tasks. K2.7's token efficiency and low price make it the obvious choice.
Bulk code generation — boilerplate, CRUD endpoints, test scaffolding, repetitive components. K2.7 generates these competently at a fraction of the cost.
Long-horizon refactoring — multi-file changes across a large codebase. K2.7 holds 256K context and stays coherent across long agentic runs.
Test writing — generating comprehensive test suites. High token volume, mechanical, perfect for K2.7.
Documentation — READMEs, API docs, inline comments. Necessary but not reasoning-intensive.
DevOps and config — Docker files, CI pipelines, deployment scripts. K2.7's MCP tool-use scored 81.1 on MCP Mark Verified, so it handles tool-calling workflows well.
First-pass anything — when you need a working draft fast and will refine later, K2.7 gives you 80% of the result for 20% of the cost.
What Goes on Claude Opus 4.8
These are the rare, high-stakes tasks where reasoning quality directly determines the outcome.
Architecture decisions — when the choice you make now determines six months of technical debt, you want the best reasoning available.
Complex debugging — the bug nobody can find, the race condition, the heisenbug. Opus 4.8's reasoning depth earns its price here.
Security-critical code — auth flows, payment handling, anything where a subtle mistake is catastrophic.
Final review — before you ship, run the critical path through Opus 4.8 to catch what K2.7 missed.
Ambiguous requirements — when the task itself is unclear and the model needs to reason about what you actually want, not just execute.
High-stakes writing — the investor email, the technical proposal, the thing that has to be right the first time.
The Workflow, Step by Step
Step 1 — Set Up Both Models
Kimi K2.7:
API at kimi.com/code/console
Model ID: kimi-k2.7-code
Or use Kimi Code CLI (terminal-first agent, plans from $19/month)
Claude Opus 4.8:
API model string: claude-opus-4-8
Or Claude Code, or the Claude apps
Set both up. You'll switch between them by task.
Step 2 — Default to Kimi
Make K2.7 your default. Every task starts here unless it clearly belongs to Opus.
This single habit is where most of the savings come from. If 80% of your tasks run on a model that costs 1/5 as much, your bill drops accordingly.
Step 3 — Escalate to Opus When It Matters
Escalate to Opus 4.8 when you hit one of these signals:
K2.7 gave you an answer and you're not confident it's right
The task is architectural, not mechanical
A mistake here would be expensive or hard to reverse
The requirements are ambiguous and need real reasoning
It's the final review before shipping
Escalation is the exception, not the rule. But when you escalate, you get the best.
Step 4 — Use Kimi to Prepare, Opus to Decide
The most powerful pattern: use K2.7 to do the heavy lifting, then Opus to make the judgment call.
Example: refactoring a large module.
K2.7:
plaintext
Read this module. Generate three different refactoring approaches with full implementations for each.
Opus 4.8: 
plaintext
Here are three refactoring approaches for the same module. Which one has the best long-term maintainability and why? What are the failure modes of each?
K2.7 does the expensive token-heavy generation. Opus does the cheap-but-critical reasoning. You get frontier-quality decisions at a fraction of the cost.
Step 5 — Final Review Always on Opus
Before anything ships to production, run the critical path through Opus 4.8:
plaintext
Review this code for correctness, security, and edge cases.
This is going to production. Be ruthless.
Focus on: what breaks under load, what breaks with malicious input, 
what breaks when a dependency fails.
List every issue by severity.
This single review catches what high-volume generation misses. It's the cheapest insurance you can buy.
A Real Example: Building a Feature End to End
Say you're building a payment integration. Here's how the two-model workflow runs:
K2.7 — Generate the API client, the data models, the request/response handlers, the test scaffolding. High volume, mechanical, cheap.
Opus 4.8 — Design the error-handling strategy for failed payments. This is where subtle reasoning matters — what happens on a timeout, a partial failure, a duplicate charge.
K2.7 — Implement the error handling Opus designed. Write the tests for every failure mode.
Opus 4.8 — Final security review of the payment path before it ships.
Four steps. Two models. The expensive reasoning happens twice, on the two decisions that actually matter. Everything else runs cheap.
The Cost Math
Let's say a typical week of active development:
The same week running everything on Opus 4.8:
15M output tokens × $25/M = $375
The same week running everything on K2.7:
15M output tokens × $4/M = $60 — but with worse architecture decisions and weaker final reviews.
The two-model split: $85. Frontier-quality decisions where it matters, cheap execution everywhere else.
That's 77% cheaper than Opus-only, while keeping Opus-quality on the decisions that determine whether your code actually works.
When to Break the Rule
Two situations where you ignore the routing:
Learning a new domain. When you don't yet know what's mechanical vs what's critical, run more through Opus until you build judgment. The savings come once you know your own work.
Truly critical projects. If you're building something where any bug is catastrophic — medical, financial infrastructure, safety systems — the cost savings aren't worth the risk. Run more through Opus.
The workflow optimizes for the common case: normal development where most tasks are routine and a few are critical.
Conclusion
The question was never "Kimi or Claude."
It's "which model for which task."
Kimi K2.7 for the high-volume mechanical work — bulk generation, refactoring, tests, docs. 30% more token-efficient than K2.6, a fraction of Opus pricing.
Claude Opus 4.8 for the rare critical decisions — architecture, security, final review, ambiguous reasoning.
Route by task. Default to cheap. Escalate when it matters.
Same output quality on the things that determine success. 77% lower bill.
That's the workflow.
